00:00:06.170 --> 00:00:07.560
KRISTIN NICHOLAS: Hi, everybody.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:09.950
I made you a Google Doodle.

00:00:09.950 --> 00:00:12.500
And it's all patterned.

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:16.490
I grew up in a family of five
girls in northern New Jersey,

00:00:16.490 --> 00:00:21.230
and textiles and fabrics
were always around.

00:00:21.230 --> 00:00:23.600
I learned to sew when
I was nine, and stitch.

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:26.150
My grandmother was a
quilter, embroiderer.

00:00:26.150 --> 00:00:28.460
And I really got
interested in it,

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:32.210
and I actually went to school
for textiles and clothing.

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:35.190
And then I got a master's in it.

00:00:35.190 --> 00:00:37.760
And for 16 years I worked
as a creative director

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:39.640
at a yarn company.

00:00:39.640 --> 00:00:41.690
And then I had my
daughter, who's here,

00:00:41.690 --> 00:00:44.240
and I decided to go freelance.

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:46.400
And I've written
12 books so far.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:49.160
This is my latest,
"Crafting a Patterned Home".

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.540
So I've got a little bit
of stuff that previews.

00:00:53.540 --> 00:00:54.340
This is our house.

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:57.530
It's a 1751 farmhouse.

00:00:57.530 --> 00:01:00.590
And it's white on the
outside, and you can't really

00:01:00.590 --> 00:01:02.490
tell what's inside it.

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:05.840
Here it is in the snow.

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:07.140
And we have a sheep farm.

00:01:07.140 --> 00:01:11.030
We have about 300 sheep,
and my husband is a farmer.

00:01:11.030 --> 00:01:12.600
He grew up on a farm.

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:17.870
And so we sell our lamb at
farmers' markets and wholesale

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:18.890
a little bit.

00:01:18.890 --> 00:01:23.540
So I'm always shuffling
around frozen meat.

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:26.450
And so the sheep graze.

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:27.760
They keep the land down.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:30.710
It was an old,
abandoned apple orchard.

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:32.210
So here's in the fall.

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:33.312
It's incredibly beautiful.

00:01:33.312 --> 00:01:35.270
I don't know if anybody's
been to western Mass,

00:01:35.270 --> 00:01:38.760
but it's really
pretty out there.

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.040
This is my pottery shed.

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:43.100
This is actually part
of the book project.

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:44.780
And here's some sunflowers.

00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:45.990
I love sunflowers.

00:01:45.990 --> 00:01:48.020
I love all kinds of
nature and flowers.

00:01:48.020 --> 00:01:52.760
I grow a lot of flowers, and
they're a big part of my work.

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:55.880
Zinnias, my favorites.

00:01:55.880 --> 00:02:00.600
And just the leaves,
all the motion.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:02.840
You can get ideas for
patterns from that.

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:06.890
The vines going around.

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:09.410
Watering can with that
beautiful heart-shaped leaf.

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:11.690
You're going to see
that a little later.

00:02:11.690 --> 00:02:12.950
Hydrangeas.

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:18.650
Beautiful pinks, browns,
greens, chartreuses.

00:02:18.650 --> 00:02:20.270
More zinnias.

00:02:20.270 --> 00:02:24.140
And for a while there, we grew
up about an acre of sunflowers,

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:25.037
and this is them.

00:02:25.037 --> 00:02:26.870
We've scaled a little
bit back because we've

00:02:26.870 --> 00:02:31.160
gone more into the
sheep, but this is them.

00:02:31.160 --> 00:02:34.700
And I still do a big garden,
half a garden of sunflowers.

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:35.960
I just love the shapes.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:38.240
And you guys probably
know what the name is

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.850
about how the seeds go around.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:41.651
I have no clue.

00:02:41.651 --> 00:02:42.650
I just know it's pretty.

00:02:45.270 --> 00:02:54.381
And here's some sheep,
lambs on pasture.

00:02:54.381 --> 00:02:54.880
More sheep.

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:58.420
This is an abandoned
apple orchard.

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:00.270
Pretty, pretty colors here.

00:03:00.270 --> 00:03:02.720
That stuff, it's a weed,
but it's so pretty.

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:08.590
So I also have
collected textiles

00:03:08.590 --> 00:03:11.020
for years and years and years.

00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:14.392
I started when I found a
piece when I was in college,

00:03:14.392 --> 00:03:15.850
and it was my first
piece I bought.

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:19.690
I can remember it
was back in the '70s,

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:21.940
and it was right
before Afghanistan

00:03:21.940 --> 00:03:23.260
was going to be taken over.

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:25.270
And I was like, I got
to get a piece of this.

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:27.940
So I still have that
piece of fabric.

00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:33.340
And this is suzani,
which is from Uzbekistan.

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:35.480
I love this motif.

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:38.440
It's all embroidered, if you can
believe it, all hand-stitched.

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:41.710
So I find the connection between
somebody hand stitching that

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:48.340
and then me using it as a motif
in my designs as a cool thing

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:49.060
to do.

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:52.840
So I do a lot of computer
stuff with digital art

00:03:52.840 --> 00:03:54.700
and use these designs.

00:03:54.700 --> 00:03:55.930
There's my sunflowers.

00:03:55.930 --> 00:03:58.520
And you're going to see more of
this room a little bit later.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:01.560
Those walls are
all hand-painted.

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:02.530
I hand painted them.

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.170
And that's a collection
of cloisonne,

00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:08.770
which is either
from Japan or China,

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:11.290
and it's enamel on brass.

00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:13.730
Beautiful colors you can get.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:16.450
So I have quite a bit of that.

00:04:16.450 --> 00:04:20.079
I love all the designs on it.

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:24.670
This is an old
antique Italian urn

00:04:24.670 --> 00:04:27.310
with dahlias in the background.

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:29.500
And you can see the other
piece of textile fabric

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:34.130
on the bottom, and
more cloisonne.

00:04:34.130 --> 00:04:37.690
So I find I can take a
bunch of flowers and some

00:04:37.690 --> 00:04:40.330
of these beautiful objects
I have and some fabrics,

00:04:40.330 --> 00:04:42.940
and I can get a design
idea just by placing

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:47.270
those things together and
then taking a photo of it.

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:49.540
And I can either paint
a picture off of it,

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:53.230
or maybe figure out
how to take two motifs

00:04:53.230 --> 00:04:57.190
and match them together
or get color ideas.

00:04:57.190 --> 00:04:58.980
And the walls there
are stenciled.

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:01.460
I hand stenciled them.

00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:03.160
Here's a bunch of
inspiration pictures.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:06.370
I'm going to go kind of fast
because I got a lot of them.

00:05:06.370 --> 00:05:08.920
This is from Portugal, ceramics.

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:12.760
This is a mola from Panama.

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:14.810
Old carpet.

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:20.560
Some transferware with
flowers and books that I think

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.930
is from India.

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:25.300
Correct me if I'm
wrong if anybody knows.

00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:26.830
This is also from India.

00:05:26.830 --> 00:05:29.110
This is incredible.

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:32.710
Every single stitch in
there is embroidered

00:05:32.710 --> 00:05:34.240
to make those motifs.

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:36.610
I mean, it's just unbelievable.

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:40.210
This is from Uzbekistan,
beautiful border treatment.

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:43.420
This is an old sleeve from--

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:46.250
I can't remember where
because I really don't know.

00:05:46.250 --> 00:05:48.700
But see the moths have
eaten a little bit of it?

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:52.840
But I just love the motif
and the border treatment.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:55.660
And then the piece
of felt up the right

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.760
that's all kind of moth eaten.

00:05:57.760 --> 00:05:59.380
Pretty idea.

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:02.500
This is a Peruvian piece.

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:05.020
This is from India,
a block print.

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:07.900
I'm crazy over these things.

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:09.980
That's another part of that.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:13.750
This is crewel work,
all stitched from India.

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:15.970
This, I have no idea
where it came from,

00:06:15.970 --> 00:06:21.340
but it's all inlaid, so it's
all carved and then inlaid.

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:25.090
And these are some
saris from India.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:27.757
So isn't that cool how
they've got the paisley design

00:06:27.757 --> 00:06:29.590
at the bottom and then
mixed with the plaid,

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:31.622
and then the medallion
piece on the top?

00:06:31.622 --> 00:06:33.580
You can take all these
ideas and then turn them

00:06:33.580 --> 00:06:35.860
into something of your own.

00:06:35.860 --> 00:06:38.950
This is a piece of ikat fabric.

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:44.350
That's another sari with
all kinds of fun sequins.

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:48.419
Another piece from India with
mirrors, all embroidered.

00:06:48.419 --> 00:06:49.460
Another piece from India.

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:55.580
This is from Uzbekistan.

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:57.050
That's the back.

00:06:57.050 --> 00:07:00.590
Lots of times these things are
so pretty in the back, too.

00:07:00.590 --> 00:07:02.400
More from India.

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:03.380
That's from Africa.

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:05.540
It's a piece of kente cloth.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:07.460
And that's a piece
of needlepoint.

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:09.941
I don't know where it's from.

00:07:09.941 --> 00:07:15.030
From India, more from
India, Uzbekistan.

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:17.330
India.

00:07:17.330 --> 00:07:20.087
And so we have a lot of
creatures at our farm.

00:07:20.087 --> 00:07:22.170
Now I'm going to tell you
a little bit about that.

00:07:22.170 --> 00:07:23.780
That's Annika the cat.

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:26.540
And that is--

00:07:26.540 --> 00:07:28.940
I don't even know what
name she was because we

00:07:28.940 --> 00:07:30.470
have a litters of kittens.

00:07:30.470 --> 00:07:32.990
And she just happened to be
doing that for the photo shoot,

00:07:32.990 --> 00:07:36.410
and it was like oh my goodness,
stripes on pattern on pattern.

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:38.960
How fabulous is that?

00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:43.170
And this, a litter of kittens
with a beautiful rug behind it

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:45.530
and crewel work.

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:47.510
That's Paisley, one
of our sheep dogs,

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:49.310
Border Collie to
round up the sheep.

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:50.930
That's Kate.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:54.290
These are two Great
Pyrenees guard dogs.

00:07:54.290 --> 00:07:58.910
They are Bo and Sadie and
they keep the coyotes away.

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:01.970
But they're
sweethearts to people.

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:06.290
And there's some
more sheep, chickens.

00:08:06.290 --> 00:08:08.840
That's the name of our farm.

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:11.540
And that's moving them.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:13.800
You have to move them,
