Well, you can see the fluid on
her and she's licking it off.

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:46.170
Sometimes I go a little
nuts and dress up my sheep.

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:47.976
So this is a ram.

00:08:47.976 --> 00:08:49.350
And I was doing
this photo shoot.

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:54.240
I had this idea to make
a sweater for a lamb.

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:56.460
And I was getting it all
ready, and my husband

00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:57.660
said, look over there.

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:01.350
This little sheep was sitting
on top of this 300 pound ram.

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:03.760
It was like oh, so cute.

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:06.030
So this is an image
that I did that's pretty

00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:08.580
popular around the internet.

00:09:08.580 --> 00:09:12.906
And so this was my 11th book,
"Crafting a Colorful Home".

00:09:12.906 --> 00:09:14.280
And now this is
the book I'm here

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:16.590
to talk about called
"Crafting a Patterned Home".

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:19.050
So all these pictures
of these projects

00:09:19.050 --> 00:09:22.260
are all things that you guys
can make if you so choose.

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:24.120
Everything's done by hand.

00:09:24.120 --> 00:09:26.320
None of the materials
are expensive.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:29.190
And as long as you get the
idea and get the nerve,

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:32.940
you can decorate your home,
or maybe decorate some fabric,

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:36.192
or do stuff for a
shirt or a tablecloth.

00:09:39.030 --> 00:09:42.130
We're going have a
little section on color.

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:46.410
And these are pieces of felt.
I love to play with colors.

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:50.550
And just by rolling
things up, you

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:52.950
can figure out what colors
work well against each other

00:09:52.950 --> 00:09:55.720
when you're putting
them together.

00:09:55.720 --> 00:09:58.460
And the same thing
you can do with yarn.

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:01.950
And you can do it with paint.

00:10:01.950 --> 00:10:05.310
Has everybody seen
a color wheel?

00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:08.070
Pretty much you learned
it when you were a kid.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.250
But I use this a lot.

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:12.510
I use it intuitively.

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:14.700
I call it a rainbow
in the round.

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:16.620
So as you can see, it
goes all the way around.

00:10:16.620 --> 00:10:18.670
It has 12 slices.

00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:24.690
And if you look opposite each
other on the color wheel,

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:26.820
those are complementary colors.

00:10:26.820 --> 00:10:28.650
If you look next to
each other, those

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:30.330
are called analogous colors.

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:32.280
And I'm going to talk
a lot about that.

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:36.240
So just try to remember.

00:10:36.240 --> 00:10:39.630
So here we have
samples that I painted.

00:10:39.630 --> 00:10:42.850
All the way to the left
are the analogous colors.

00:10:42.850 --> 00:10:47.310
So they're like orange,
yellow, and red orange.

00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:49.890
In the center, we've got the
complementary colors, so blue

00:10:49.890 --> 00:10:50.484
and violet.

00:10:50.484 --> 00:10:51.900
And to the right
we have something

00:10:51.900 --> 00:10:53.040
that I call tonal colors.

00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:54.960
So it's like shades of blue.

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:58.080
And so you can think about
what you like the best

00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:01.447
and use that in your
home in different places,

00:11:01.447 --> 00:11:03.030
depending on the
mood you want to get.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:08.060
This is another good
way to work with color

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:11.000
is have just a piece of
paper in the background,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.970
and then just get a
flower or something

00:11:13.970 --> 00:11:17.750
and see how the colors
work against each other.

00:11:17.750 --> 00:11:22.130
So this is what I call
analogous because they're all

00:11:22.130 --> 00:11:22.880
sort of related.

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:25.130
It goes from the
chartreuse to the yellow

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:29.600
and then to the orange.

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:31.495
And this is getting
a little bit away

00:11:31.495 --> 00:11:33.620
from that because it's got
the hot pink background.

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:35.911
But you can see the same
flowers, how different they're

00:11:35.911 --> 00:11:37.520
starting to look.

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:42.110
This is on blue, on a brighter
blue, so this is complementary.

00:11:42.110 --> 00:11:44.810
You see how they're popping?

00:11:44.810 --> 00:11:48.344
And then that's a little bit
more subdued, bluish gray.

00:11:48.344 --> 00:11:49.510
And here it is in real life.

00:11:53.190 --> 00:11:56.990
This is a complementary color
combination in fabulous yellow,

00:11:56.990 --> 00:12:00.050
purple, green.

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:02.155
And here it is on furniture.

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:07.980
This is our house.

00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:10.860
And so I use a lot of
pattern in the house.

00:12:10.860 --> 00:12:15.090
It has, actually,
very light gray walls.

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:19.880
And then I mix
fabrics, colors, and--

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:22.050
whoops, there we go--

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:25.510
pottery, all these
things with it.

00:12:25.510 --> 00:12:29.160
So I used the very
light gray wall,

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:31.630
and then brought the patterns
in, first with the pottery

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:32.755
and then with more fabrics.

00:12:35.360 --> 00:12:38.660
This is the living room.

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:41.970
So you probably can't
see it, but this

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:44.270
is a tonal living room.

00:12:44.270 --> 00:12:47.540
I actually have
chartreuse and gold walls

00:12:47.540 --> 00:12:48.860
and mixed with green.

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:50.750
Actually, it's analogous.

00:12:50.750 --> 00:12:53.300
But then, by bringing in
all the different patterns

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:57.360
and the different fabrics,
it looks differently.

00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:59.030
It starts to become
complementary

00:12:59.030 --> 00:13:01.370
because the oranges and
the reds are popping off

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:03.466
the green and the yellow.

00:13:03.466 --> 00:13:05.840
And so then you start mixing
all these different patterns

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:11.000
together and you get what I
find very pleasing and cozy

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.100
and warm by mixing
all the colors.

00:13:14.100 --> 00:13:16.710
There's another view.

00:13:16.710 --> 00:13:17.420
Oh.

