00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:37.050
I'll do it myself.

00:14:37.050 --> 00:14:40.360
So I painted the walls
to look like wallpaper.

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:44.004
And it took a couple
days, but it actually

00:14:44.004 --> 00:14:46.170
is pretty because there's
all these little different

00:14:46.170 --> 00:14:49.330
variations in it where wallpaper
would be screen printed

00:14:49.330 --> 00:14:52.511
and just look pretty flat.

00:14:52.511 --> 00:14:53.010
OK.

00:14:53.010 --> 00:14:54.676
We're going to talk
about some patterns.

00:14:57.210 --> 00:15:01.440
So does anybody
think about patterns?

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:04.770
Patterns, to me, are like so--

00:15:04.770 --> 00:15:06.250
I just love them.

00:15:06.250 --> 00:15:07.800
They're so inspirational.

00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:09.030
They just make me feel happy.

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:10.420
The simplest one is a polka dot.

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:12.750
You guys all did polka
dots when you were kids,

00:15:12.750 --> 00:15:15.280
and here's different
bunches of polka dots.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:19.530
So we've got little pin dots,
bigger dots, random spaced,

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:23.790
spaced out, and
alternating stripes.

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:25.320
Next thing.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:27.300
Simple stripe, but
you can move on

00:15:27.300 --> 00:15:28.770
and keep changing the stripes.

00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:31.890
So you see all the
variations you can do?

00:15:31.890 --> 00:15:35.490
Just hand drawn.

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:38.310
And then if you take a stripe
and you turn it on its side,

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:40.320
you've got a plaid or a check.

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:42.840
So this is just a natural
progression of patterns

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:44.157
and how you can make them.

00:15:44.157 --> 00:15:45.990
And you can see all the
different variations

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:47.760
you can get.

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:51.030
If you take it and twist
it on the diagonal,

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:53.460
twist it 45 degrees,
you've got a diagonal.

00:15:53.460 --> 00:15:56.640
And then if you start
cutting them into segments

00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:00.420
and you start flipping them
around, you've got chevrons,

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:02.070
and you've got a trellis design.

00:16:02.070 --> 00:16:03.660
And so these are
all motifs that are

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:06.810
used in all kinds of
wallpapers and fabrics.

00:16:06.810 --> 00:16:07.920
I mean, we look around.

00:16:07.920 --> 00:16:09.270
This room is awesome.

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:12.510
You've got all these gorgeous
plaid fabrics, which--

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:16.480
it's a pattern, but there's
so many different variations.

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:18.900
This next section,
this is geometrics.

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:21.690
So they're squares
and rectangles,

00:16:21.690 --> 00:16:25.860
putting them in between
stripes and you make a pattern.

00:16:25.860 --> 00:16:30.330
More geometric circles,
hexagons, triangles, diamonds,

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:31.410
ovals.

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:33.600
So you see how
there's a lot that you

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:36.870
can do with simple
motifs to make a pattern.

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:39.480
And then these are
called organic motifs.

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:44.970
And they're more
round and organic--

00:16:44.970 --> 00:16:50.790
tulips, hearts, paisleys, one
of my favorite things, flowers.

00:16:50.790 --> 00:16:54.720
And here we have organic
motifs, more in striped patterns

00:16:54.720 --> 00:16:57.810
and borders, combining them.

00:16:57.810 --> 00:17:00.480
And this is called
a figurative motif.

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:03.300
And that would be something if
you see Christmas or Halloween

00:17:03.300 --> 00:17:06.810
wallpaper, they
take little objects

00:17:06.810 --> 00:17:09.540
and make patterns out of them.

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:14.010
Here, this is how different
patterns are made.

00:17:14.010 --> 00:17:16.290
We can have a lot of white
space in the background,

00:17:16.290 --> 00:17:20.069
and this is very dots on dots.

00:17:20.069 --> 00:17:22.109
Then we can have a
bigger dot, and so you

00:17:22.109 --> 00:17:25.290
have a whole different
feeling from the dots when

00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:29.080
you change the sizes
and change the backdrop.

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:33.120
Now here we can have them
so they're spaced out

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:36.120
and you get a random pattern.

00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:37.680
But you've still
got the coverage

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:39.480
on the one on the
right, and the other one

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:41.210
is very open and loose.

00:17:41.210 --> 00:17:42.840
And it gives a
different feeling.

00:17:42.840 --> 00:17:47.140
It'll give a different feeling
to a fabric, to a room.

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:49.440
This is pattern repeats.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:53.380
You can see a straight repeat
up on the left, top left.

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:56.730
And if you move to the right,
you can see a brick repeat,

00:17:56.730 --> 00:18:00.150
looks like a brick pattern that
you see all the time in Boston.

00:18:00.150 --> 00:18:02.910
To the left on the bottom,
that's called a half drop,

00:18:02.910 --> 00:18:05.880
so the circles move down a half.

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:07.950
And then we have
a random repeat.

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:11.100
So that's basically fabric
design and wallpaper design.

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:12.280
That's what you do.

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:15.240
And if you do it on
a computer, you just

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:20.640
move it with numbers, which
is what I do a lot of.

