so I took the square idea,
turned it on its side,

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:31.820
made it a diagonal, and made
almost like an argyle tile

00:26:31.820 --> 00:26:36.200
design, and then
painted some vases

00:26:36.200 --> 00:26:37.830
with flowers on top of it.

00:26:37.830 --> 00:26:40.670
And you can see the fabrics
that I've used on the top.

00:26:40.670 --> 00:26:42.990
Those are things
that you saw earlier.

00:26:42.990 --> 00:26:45.455
They're from Uzbekistan,
the embroidered pieces.

00:26:48.410 --> 00:26:50.780
In the past I've been
known for knitting,

00:26:50.780 --> 00:26:52.700
so I had to put a
knitting thing in.

00:26:52.700 --> 00:26:56.850
And that is-- let's see.

00:26:56.850 --> 00:26:59.420
Right here, OK.

00:26:59.420 --> 00:27:03.120
Pillow that's not sewed,
it travels better.

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:06.330
So it's just you follow a chart.

00:27:06.330 --> 00:27:08.300
Is anybody a knitter here?

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:09.120
Oh, there we go.

00:27:09.120 --> 00:27:10.020
OK, good.

00:27:10.020 --> 00:27:11.240
So you guys know this.

00:27:11.240 --> 00:27:13.040
And follow the chart.

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:18.290
And then these little bits are
added on later in embroidery.

00:27:18.290 --> 00:27:18.790
Yeah.

00:27:22.817 --> 00:27:25.025
Here you can see the chair
with the different colors.

00:27:27.710 --> 00:27:29.980
So the khaki and the red.

00:27:29.980 --> 00:27:33.725
And on the side I used
a yellow just for fun.

00:27:33.725 --> 00:27:35.930
And most people aren't
even going to see this.

00:27:35.930 --> 00:27:37.730
But for me it's fun.

00:27:37.730 --> 00:27:38.270
OK.

00:27:38.270 --> 00:27:44.000
Upstairs in the bathroom I had
yellow walls that were color

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.770
washed.

00:27:46.770 --> 00:27:51.020
So for this design I made
long, eight-inch stripes

00:27:51.020 --> 00:27:52.770
because my ruler
was eight inches.

00:27:52.770 --> 00:27:56.160
Lots of times I just do
things that are really easy.

00:27:56.160 --> 00:28:02.600
And then I cut this ogee
pattern out and traced around it

00:28:02.600 --> 00:28:04.520
with a pencil, and
then just filled it

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:06.560
in with streaky paint.

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:09.270
And this picture
is really popular.

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:10.790
It's been on the
internet a bunch.

00:28:10.790 --> 00:28:17.000
And the bathtub, I was
inspired by embroidery.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:20.360
So I just took some white
paint and just did sort of

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:22.280
like a flower design on it.

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:25.370
It took less than an hour.

00:28:25.370 --> 00:28:30.410
And then I put the border on
the bottom on the wood stand.

00:28:30.410 --> 00:28:33.770
And you can see that
little sun design,

00:28:33.770 --> 00:28:37.730
which I actually got off of
this tile that was on the walls.

00:28:40.910 --> 00:28:43.290
I wanted do some things
that were really easy.

00:28:43.290 --> 00:28:45.090
This is called combing.

00:28:45.090 --> 00:28:46.840
You take a piece of cardboard.

00:28:46.840 --> 00:28:49.800
You cut it so it
looks like a comb.

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:53.340
You paint one color
on a piece of wood.

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:55.560
So I painted it blue.

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:59.700
Then I painted it white,
and while it was still wet,

00:28:59.700 --> 00:29:02.490
I took the piece of cardboard
that looked like a comb

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:05.880
and just dragged it through
in this kind of swirly design.

00:29:05.880 --> 00:29:10.230
So except for the
waiting for it to dry,

00:29:10.230 --> 00:29:13.054
this project was probably 40
minutes or something like that

00:29:13.054 --> 00:29:14.220
after I got the paint on it.

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:19.830
So I like sunflowers.

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:23.610
So this is the
sunflower bedroom.

00:29:23.610 --> 00:29:26.310
I did it in the winter when
it was really, really gray.

00:29:26.310 --> 00:29:32.020
And I thought, oh, let's do
some overblown sunflowers.

00:29:32.020 --> 00:29:37.680
So I just took a big piece of 18
by 24 paper, folded it in four,

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:39.390
and then just cut
some shapes out.

00:29:39.390 --> 00:29:44.940
And I used them as a template,
and I drew with pencil around

00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:47.070
and left space for the leaves.

00:29:47.070 --> 00:29:50.250
So I painted them all
in a light yellow.

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:53.940
Then I went back and added some
leaves, free form leaves where

00:29:53.940 --> 00:29:57.540
it needed to be, so
there was a lot of space

00:29:57.540 --> 00:30:01.410
available around the
flowers, and then

00:30:01.410 --> 00:30:03.240
put sort of a wash
for the center

00:30:03.240 --> 00:30:04.940
and outlined it all
in a dark brown.

00:30:07.780 --> 00:30:09.940
And it just makes me happy.

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:13.030
And in one end of the
room, to calm it all down,

00:30:13.030 --> 00:30:16.930
I put this pretty spring green
because the maple leaves--

00:30:16.930 --> 00:30:18.830
you know that one day
when they come out

00:30:18.830 --> 00:30:20.350
and it's just gorgeous?

00:30:20.350 --> 00:30:22.150
So that's what this color is.

00:30:22.150 --> 00:30:25.120
So in the winter I can look
at that and say, oh yeah,

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:26.890
one day spring will be here.

00:30:26.890 --> 00:30:29.920
But it just gives it a nice--

00:30:29.920 --> 00:30:31.240
like a break.

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:33.340
And then I put these
antique engravings

00:30:33.340 --> 00:30:37.600
on the wall and all the books.

00:30:37.600 --> 00:30:39.160
There's another
corner of the room.

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:42.820
That's an oil painting I did,
and also lampshade I painted.

00:30:42.820 --> 00:30:47.200
I do a lot of
lampshade paintings.

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:49.120
On the other wall
there's closets,

00:30:49.120 --> 00:30:51.220
and I thought,
OK, I need to have

00:30:51.220 --> 00:30:57.860
something that's more geometric
to stand off these sunflowers.

00:30:57.860 --> 00:31:02.140
So I came up with this
idea of big diamonds.

00:31:02.140 --> 00:31:06.520
And I put tape in
a diamond form,

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:09.820
and I just sponged it
with a piece of sponge

00:31:09.820 --> 00:31:12.760
to get kind of the mottled edge.

00:31:12.760 --> 00:31:17.680
And it's another part
of the room that's

00:31:17.680 --> 00:31:20.620
like geometric versus organic.

00:31:20.620 --> 00:31:23.230
And as you move around the
room, it has different feelings.

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:25.690
And it all sort
of mixes together.

00:31:25.690 --> 00:31:28.180
This is a bedspread that I did.

00:31:28.180 --> 00:31:32.260
It's quilting, because this book
is for all kinds of crafters.

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:36.490
So this is pieced.

00:31:36.490 --> 00:31:41.271
And I used an idea-- the Amish
people are incredible quilters,

00:31:41.271 --> 00:31:43.270
and way back when they
used to do a lot of stuff

00:31:43.270 --> 00:31:45.820
with these beautiful
bright colors of wool.

00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:52.430
And this was inspired off
that, very simple shapes.

00:31:52.430 --> 00:32:00.150
The back of it,
this is a linocut

00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:04.170
that I carved into Speedy
Carve, it's called,

00:32:04.170 --> 00:32:05.550
so I used a carving knife.

00:32:05.550 --> 00:32:09.540
And I printed it in black
and then I scanned it.

00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:11.730
Then I brought it
into Illustrator.

00:32:11.730 --> 00:32:16.110
And then I made the
fabric for the backing

00:32:16.110 --> 00:32:17.835
and mixed up all the
different colors.

00:32:17.835 --> 00:32:19.335
So you don't really
see it, but it's

00:32:19.335 --> 00:32:21.780
a way you can add
little bits of surprises

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:24.810
and take these
hand painting ideas

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:29.299
and put them into use
in the computer world.

00:32:29.299 --> 00:32:30.840
There's a company
called Spoon Flower

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:31.890
that's out of North Carolina.

00:32:31.890 --> 00:32:33.306
I don't know if
you know about it.

00:32:33.306 --> 00:32:36.240
But that's where I get
this stuff printed.

00:32:36.240 --> 00:32:40.140
And then another thing, for
a little bit of visual rest,

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:43.350
is these giant polka
dots that were hand

00:32:43.350 --> 00:32:45.540
printed on a piece of linen.

00:32:45.540 --> 00:32:48.390
And I called this--

00:32:48.390 --> 00:32:50.410
I was thinking about
big and little dots,

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:52.170
so I did these
giant dots and then

00:32:52.170 --> 00:32:55.050
put French knots, which is
an embroidery technique,

00:32:55.050 --> 00:32:57.690
around it in a different
color, and I backed it

00:32:57.690 --> 00:32:59.940
in this fun color.

00:32:59.940 --> 00:33:05.190
So you know, you can do this
stuff at night when you're, I

00:33:05.190 --> 00:33:08.610
don't know, trying to cool down.

00:33:08.610 --> 00:33:09.670
This is the dining room.

00:33:09.670 --> 00:33:14.580
This is all painted walls,
and then down below it's

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:16.400
a plaid design.

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:21.060
More of the dining room
with my oil paintings

00:33:21.060 --> 00:33:22.590
and mixing the fabrics in.

00:33:25.220 --> 00:33:32.090
These are tiles that I actually
painted and glazed and fired

00:33:32.090 --> 00:33:33.770
and put on a piece
of cement board

00:33:33.770 --> 00:33:37.180
and mounted them into the
wall onto the fireplace.

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:41.890
And these are some
projects outside.

00:33:41.890 --> 00:33:43.339
You know she sheds are a term?

00:33:43.339 --> 00:33:45.130
I don't know if anybody
has heard about it.

00:33:45.130 --> 00:33:47.110
But it's a term so
these are she sheds,

00:33:47.110 --> 00:33:57.100
and these have vines and a fun
painted rug and printed fabric.

00:33:57.100 --> 00:34:00.070
And this is my pottery shed.

00:34:00.070 --> 00:34:05.260
So I used vinyl VCT tiles on
the floors in bright colors.

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:10.120
And there's the floor
and the cat, Charlie.

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:15.635
And I just did this around the
edges, stamped with sponges.

00:34:15.635 --> 00:34:17.260
And I used different
colors all the way

00:34:17.260 --> 00:34:19.929
around the room for more fun
because it doesn't really

00:34:19.929 --> 00:34:21.130
have to match.

00:34:21.130 --> 00:34:25.088
And that's a
hand-printed linocut.

00:34:25.088 --> 00:34:26.379
And there's some of my pottery.

00:34:29.290 --> 00:34:32.330
More greenware patterns.

00:34:32.330 --> 00:34:35.889
And this is a sourcebook I got.

00:34:35.889 --> 00:34:37.300
I don't know where it's from.

00:34:37.300 --> 00:34:38.270
I can't understand it.

00:34:38.270 --> 00:34:40.480
It's got some kind
of weird writing.

00:34:40.480 --> 00:34:42.159
But I love that.

00:34:42.159 --> 00:34:44.889
This was probably given
as a guide for people

00:34:44.889 --> 00:34:48.340
to do embroidery way
back when somewhere.

00:34:48.340 --> 00:34:50.260
This is a lamp from Home Depot.

00:34:50.260 --> 00:34:53.350
I spray painted it and
then put squiggles on it.

00:34:53.350 --> 00:34:56.170
And that's the outside.

00:34:56.170 --> 00:35:01.420
I did a little bit of
mural and-- oh, more.

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:02.020
OK.

00:35:02.020 --> 00:35:04.228
There's that leaf I showed
you in the very beginning,

00:35:04.228 --> 00:35:07.480
the morning glory leaf, with
others, and a picnic down

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:11.085
in the orchard with
different projects.

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:18.160
This is the last bit.

00:35:18.160 --> 00:35:23.710
This is a cocktail
hour under the pergola.

00:35:23.710 --> 00:35:26.770
And I did this big,
big, oversized kind

00:35:26.770 --> 00:35:31.210
of Matisse-inspired
circular tabletop.

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:36.550
And I free-handed
the leaf design,

00:35:36.550 --> 00:35:43.540
and then I mixed it with
some more gridded designs

00:35:43.540 --> 00:35:46.810
and then these napkins that
are just all hand-painted.

00:35:46.810 --> 00:35:48.850
And they're scattered
around the room.

00:35:48.850 --> 00:35:50.980
They're hand-painted stripes.

00:35:50.980 --> 00:35:52.900
So does anybody
have any questions?

00:35:52.900 --> 00:35:56.200
AUDIENCE: So what I like about
this photo is that the table is

00:35:56.200 --> 00:35:59.950
really sort of free form,
but then the photos in the,

00:35:59.950 --> 00:36:04.930
I guess prints in the
background are very orderly.

00:36:04.930 --> 00:36:08.920
And so the balance or
contrast there is really nice.

00:36:08.920 --> 00:36:13.125
How do you think about
balancing that, and having

00:36:13.125 --> 00:36:14.500
some things that
are sort of more

00:36:14.500 --> 00:36:17.864
structured and formulaic
with some things that are

00:36:17.864 --> 00:36:19.030
a little bit more free form?

00:36:19.030 --> 00:36:20.238
KRISTIN NICHOLAS: It's a mix.

00:36:20.238 --> 00:36:26.650
So I usually will
start with a fabric,

00:36:26.650 --> 00:36:28.850
and then have some
kind of busy fabric.

00:36:28.850 --> 00:36:31.870
Say if I'm doing a room, and
that will be the color idea.

00:36:31.870 --> 00:36:34.840
And then I pick a
backdrop and then

00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:38.020
just keep adding things in.

00:36:38.020 --> 00:36:44.560
This table and the rug, the
table is organic, right?

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:47.045
The pictures on the
wall are very square,

00:36:47.045 --> 00:36:48.670
but when you get up
close, they're not.

00:36:48.670 --> 00:36:51.010
They're also little pictures.

00:36:51.010 --> 00:36:53.230
And then the rug is a base.

00:36:53.230 --> 00:36:56.200
And a lot of this is
done in photography.

00:36:56.200 --> 00:37:02.590
So when you're photographing
projects like I do,

00:37:02.590 --> 00:37:04.360
you have to make the
picture look good.

00:37:04.360 --> 00:37:06.700
So you're looking
through the viewfinder

00:37:06.700 --> 00:37:09.730
and balancing it all
out, making a mix.

00:37:09.730 --> 00:37:12.160
And sometimes you might
move a set all the way

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:14.170
across the room to
a different color.

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:18.550
So that rug is usually
not under that table,

00:37:18.550 --> 00:37:21.310
but it made the
picture work good.

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:24.730
And it's just trial and
error and experience.

00:37:24.730 --> 00:37:27.430
I can't tell you
the magic formula.

00:37:27.430 --> 00:37:29.320
I've been doing
this for so long.

00:37:29.320 --> 00:37:33.850
But anyway, I don't
know if I helped you.

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:42.150
AUDIENCE: So a first question
is when you painted the wall

00:37:42.150 --> 00:37:45.350
with the red crosses
and stuff, did you

00:37:45.350 --> 00:37:47.070
use the stencils for that?

00:37:47.070 --> 00:37:52.470
KRISTIN NICHOLAS: No, I used
FedEx boxes because I had them.

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:56.710
They're good, stiff cardboard,
so I cut the shapes out of them

00:37:56.710 --> 00:38:01.450
and traced around it just
with a leaded pencil,

00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:04.930
and then filled it
in with a paintbrush.

00:38:04.930 --> 00:38:05.771
AUDIENCE: I see.

00:38:05.771 --> 00:38:07.520
KRISTIN NICHOLAS: I
don't like stenciling.

00:38:07.520 --> 00:38:11.380
You have to be really neat,
and I'm not very neat.

00:38:11.380 --> 00:38:13.640
If you put the
plastic stencil on,

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:14.890
sometimes it seeps underneath.

00:38:14.890 --> 00:38:15.931
You have to clean it off.

00:38:15.931 --> 00:38:18.057
It's just this is faster for me.

00:38:18.057 --> 00:38:18.890
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:38:18.890 --> 00:38:20.584
Well, it looked perfect.

00:38:20.584 --> 00:38:22.250
KRISTIN NICHOLAS: And
if I stenciled it,

00:38:22.250 --> 00:38:23.560
it wouldn't have been perfect.

00:38:23.560 --> 00:38:24.726
It would have been a hassle.

00:38:24.726 --> 00:38:25.870
AUDIENCE: Probably.

00:38:25.870 --> 00:38:30.250
And second question is, you
said you print your fabrics.

00:38:30.250 --> 00:38:31.464
So what is the technique?

00:38:31.464 --> 00:38:32.380
How do you print them?

00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:34.180
I know you print them
digitally, but when

00:38:34.180 --> 00:38:37.220
you do it at home and on
your own, how do you do that?

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:38.830
KRISTIN NICHOLAS:
I have an iPad Pro

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:43.060
and I use a program called
Procreate, which is $9.99.

00:38:43.060 --> 00:38:46.580
And I have an Apple Pencil
and I just start drawing.

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:47.920
And I use the different brushes.

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:51.320
I get a design, like a motif
that I'm interested in,

00:38:51.320 --> 00:38:55.030
and then I bring it into
Illustrator, do Live Trace,

00:38:55.030 --> 00:38:59.650
and start building
files in Illustrator,

00:38:59.650 --> 00:39:02.824
whether I want a straight
repeat, a half drop, a brick,

00:39:02.824 --> 00:39:04.240
just start fooling
around with it.

00:39:04.240 --> 00:39:05.770
So it's sort of a combination.

00:39:05.770 --> 00:39:08.080
Sometimes I'll actually
draw something.

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:09.650
Or these things
that I showed you I

00:39:09.650 --> 00:39:12.010
actually printed them,
scanned them, and then

00:39:12.010 --> 00:39:13.329
brought them into Illustrator.

00:39:13.329 --> 00:39:13.870
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:39:13.870 --> 00:39:16.990
So do you do hand
print them by yourself,

00:39:16.990 --> 00:39:18.590
or it's all through Illustrator?

00:39:18.590 --> 00:39:20.256
KRISTIN NICHOLAS:
That digital printing,

00:39:20.256 --> 00:39:22.510
I send it to Spoon
Flower, send them a file,

00:39:22.510 --> 00:39:23.670
and it comes in two weeks.

00:39:23.670 --> 00:39:25.090
And you can get a yard.

00:39:25.090 --> 00:39:26.836
You can actually
get a half a yard.

00:39:26.836 --> 00:39:28.210
It's amazing what
you can do now.

00:39:28.210 --> 00:39:29.155
AUDIENCE: Yeah, that's great.

00:39:29.155 --> 00:39:29.410
KRISTIN NICHOLAS: Yeah.

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:31.090
So I'm really
interested in that now.

00:39:31.090 --> 00:39:32.437
It's cool.

00:39:32.437 --> 00:39:33.520
You can reach more people.

00:39:36.220 --> 00:39:38.686
So I'm hoping that
people will really

00:39:38.686 --> 00:39:40.810
want to try some of this
stuff by hand because it's

00:39:40.810 --> 00:39:43.870
really, really easy and
doesn't take much time.

00:39:43.870 --> 00:39:47.260
But it's A, finding the time,
B, getting the supplies, which

00:39:47.260 --> 00:39:51.160
I've tried to make things that
you have around your house,

00:39:51.160 --> 00:39:54.760
and then just doing it,
getting the nerve to do it.

00:39:54.760 --> 00:39:57.070
That, I find, is most
people's problem.

00:39:57.070 --> 00:39:58.870
They don't have the nerve.

00:39:58.870 --> 00:40:00.880
So that's why I help people.

00:40:00.880 --> 00:40:04.090
I teach classes and
help them get over

